What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 113,937 loan entries with 14 features (previously 81). Less than half of the features are of type object(string) eg. LoanStatus, BorrowerState, etc while the rest is numerical. There are 12 categories of loan status:

  • Current
  • Completed
  • Chargedoff
  • Defaulted
  • Past Due (1-15 days)
  • Past Due (31-60 days)
  • Past Due (61-90 days)
  • Past Due (91-120 days)
  • Past Due (16-30 days)
  • FinalPaymentInProgress
  • Past Due (>120 days)
  • Cancelled

Listing category contains the category of the listing that the borrower selected when posting their listing: 0 - Not Available, 1 - Debt Consolidation, 2 - Home Improvement, 3 - Business, 4 - Personal Loan, 5 - Student Use, 6 - Auto, 7- Other, 8 - Baby&Adoption, 9 - Boat, 10 - Cosmetic Procedure, 11 - Engagement Ring, 12 - Green Loans, 13 - Household Expenses, 14 - Large Purchases, 15 - Medical/Dental, 16 - Motorcycle, 17 - RV, 18 - Taxes, 19 - Vacation, 20 - Wedding Loans.

ProsperScore is custom risk score built using historical Prosper data. The score ranges from 1-10, with 10 being the best, or lowest risk score. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009. BorrowerState is a two letter abbreviation of the state of the address of the burrower eg. CA means California.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

What features determine the loan amount. I'd also like to discover the state that has the most loan and reasons for it.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I believe income range, occupation and employment status will play a huge role in determining the size of the loan. I also suspect that prosper score can help to predict loan status. Ownership of house may have an effect but to a smaller degree.

# define functions to plot multiple categorical variables and single variables
def plot_categorical_variables(variables, order=None):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=len(variables), figsize = [20,20])
    for i in range(len(variables)):
        var = variables[i]
        if var == 'IncomeRange':
            sb.countplot(data = df, y = var, color = sb.color_palette()[0], ax = ax[i], order=order, orient='h')
            continue
        sb.countplot(data = df, y = var, color = sb.color_palette()[0], ax = ax[i])
        
def plot_one_categorical_var(data, var, orientation=None, hue=None, palette=None, ax=None, color=None):
    sb.countplot(data = data, y = var, color=color, hue=hue, palette=palette, ax=ax) if orientation == 'y' \
    else sb.countplot(data = data, x = var, color=color, hue=hue, palette=palette, ax=ax)

In [21]:
#select the states in chunks of five and plot it
fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=10, figsize = [30,90])
count = 0
for i in range(0, len(states), 5):
    x = i
    if x == 45:
        data = df_select.loc[(df_select.BorrowerState.isin(list(states[x:x+6])))]
        plot_one_categorical_var(data, 'ListingCategory (numeric)', hue = 'BorrowerState', ax = ax[count])
        ax[count].set(yticks=range(0,10000, 2000), yticklabels=[i for i in range(0,10000, 2000)])
        break
    data = df_select.loc[(df_select['BorrowerState'].isin(list(states[x:x+5])))]
    plot_one_categorical_var(data, 'ListingCategory (numeric)', hue = 'BorrowerState', ax = ax[count])
    ax[count].set(yticks=range(0,10000, 2000), yticklabels=[i for i in range(0,10000, 2000)])
    count = count + 1

Conclusions¶

  • Number of prior loans has a negative correlation with loan amount.
  • Higher Income range has more access to Loans.
  • Home owners get a higher loan amount.
  • There is debt pandemic in California. The slay lifestyle must be sweating lots of em.
